column1: Who will win Uganda's next presidential election?
column5: ['Yoweri Museveni', 'Amama Mbabazi', 'Kizza Besigye', 'None of the above']
column6: ['Non-US Politics']
column11: Sign up and enter your own forecast, to compete in The Economist's World in 2016 Challenge! Uganda's Yoweri Museveni is running for a fifth presidential term in an election scheduled for 18 February 2016, one of several elections in Africa next year that will test countries' commitments to democracy (The World in 2016, Reuters, Washington Post, New Vision). If a runoff is required, the end date of the question will be extended. Recommended Questions Will a member of the National League for Democracy (NLD) take office as president of Myanmar before April 2016?

column6: Foreign Policy article on why candidates are campaigning so hard in an election with a foregone conclusion:

Museveni is unlikely to die in the next 5 hours, and nothing out of the ordinary has happened in the months leading up to the election - the government has displayed typical anti-democratic behaviour and there's a good chance the whole thing is rigged anyway. Polls are putting Museveni's popularity at nearly twice that of Mbabazi, with Besigye far behind. This one seems pretty simple.

It's a little startling to see that the GJ consensus forecasts are now showing up in the very news sources I use to make forecasts[1]! There's a danger here, of course. Recall Wittgenstein's aside, “As if someone were to buy several copies of the morning newspaper to assure himself that what it said was true"[2]. But I'm pretty sure that we're not in much jeopardy yet.
Everyone seems thinks the fix is in. But little sign of life for Besigye

Museveni has gotten rid of term limits, and has maintained the presidency of Uganda for several decades. There has yet to be a serious threat to his power, and it is very unlikely he will lose the current presidential election cycle.

Status quo in the absence of credible alternatives who have had a chance to campaign effectively: "The failure of the opposition to field a joint candidate after talks in October 2015 is one factor, and the desire to maintain stability another."
Outside View: Latest opinion poll YM 54% AM 15% KB 19% Rest 12% January Opinion Poll YM 51% AM 12% KB 32% Rest 5% The opinion poll had a margin of error of +/-5%.
Violence erupts as Besigye supporters clash with police; Besigye briefly detained. Will the election be rigged?
Oposition leaders are getting arrested... there is no way YM is going to lose this election. Rather sad, really.

I feel kind of satisfaction that by arresting Besigye it was confirmed that he is the candidate that poses bigger risk for Museveni... Lowering him by 2% anyway... That one percent is only for showing my sympathies for being arrested (and in case YM dies tomorrow)

With Besigye getting arrested and two days left, I have to take away even the 1% I had left for Mbabazi. It is clear that YM will ensure that he wins. I rate the chance of a "divine coup," to use the old Nigerian joke, at less than 1% over the next two days.
Three factors for my forecast:
Following consensus, dropping Other and minimal chances for AM & KB

The passage of time with no real pro-opposition news has convinced me to up Museveni up from 94% to 99%. The most recent poll ( @pythagoras ), despite likely problems, convinces me to put my whole not-Museveni probability on Kizza Besigye.
The power of incumbency in Africa. Assuming he is alive, YM wins.
Updating for passage of time

As we've drawn closer to the date, nothing has come out that suggests Besigye or Mbabazi have gained strength. At the same time, the police have been gathering riot gear in preparation for post-election violence. Experience tells me that this is for suppression of opposition protests following the election. The state apparatus is preparing to physically guard its victory. I'm not suggesting that the elections are completely fixed, but there seems to be an expectation of a win by the incumbent. This causes me to raise my forecast for Museveni.
An opinion poll (to be taken with a large grain of salt) out of Uganda today:
A coup is always possible.
Here's to hoping the fix is in ; )

Museveni has shown his power and control over the Ugandan institutions in the past. For instance, he got the constitution amended in order to run for a third time in office in 2006. Although western support is slowly deteriorating, if there are any changes to be seen in Ugandan democracy, we should probably wait a little bit in the future. Corruption remains a huge problem in Africa, and this is likely to favor ruling parties (given that democratic process is not likely to be transparent and power structures have incentives to maintain the status quo). Voters' apathy will be another mitigation for change, turnout has been decreasing consistently ever since 1996 and is likely to be lower this year, again, this favors ruling parties statistically. Moreover, a poll published in late 2015 showed that 45% of Ugandans don't believe electoral process can lead to a power change. I understand that Museveni has the army on his side, which is also a major advantage. History shows that leaders such as Museveni are separated of their charge with the use of violence and not by voting.
I've made my bed by this point so I'll have to sleep in it.

A poll from June of 2015 indicated Museveni would get over 70% of the vote. Some claimed the poll was distorted and it is dated, but another poll put up similar numbers. Even if it was distorted, there is a lot of room for error in that poll and Museveni would win in a land slide.

I am okay with an extension for a runoff, but what if Museveni decides to be president-for-life and dispense with elections entirely? The "next presidential election" could be 20 years from now. The world does not consist entirely of binary outcomes in all things.
Update to be above consensus

AllAfrica has an interesting perspective: "If the widespread assumption that the Museveni state machinery is going to rig the elections is true, then the hectic campaigns by the Museveni team do not indicate that."* The idea seems to be this: If Museveni was simply going to rig the election, then he wouldn't need to bother with large scale campaigning. And he _is_ bothering. So he isn't going to rig the election.
http://geeskaafrika.com/2016/02/05/uganda-how-next-election-will-be-won/

The huge spending by the current president will make the difference. Local media indicate that is outspending Mbabazi by a rate of 7 to 1 (in dollars they say) here is link http://www.ibtimes.com/uganda-presidential-election-2016-museveni-spent-7m-campaign-two-months-report-says-2276699

I judge that the incumbent president is pretty sure of winning, allowing even to deploy a biometric system to increase transparency. Also the Commonwealth observer group gives me more assurance to the same. http://www.newschannel10.com/story/31163478/uganda-deploys-biometric-technology-to-improve-general-election-transparency http://www.newvision.co.ug/new_vision/news/1416460/olusegun-obasanjo-head-commonwealth-election-observers-uganda
The incumbent will manipulate the system and ensure that he wins
I always do what @cdob63 does, just not as well - self-admittedly. I was late to the is question so thank you @Pstauble, @clinton, and @Bismarc for the analysis.

This would be Museveni's 5th time to be elected in a country that Freedom House has rated "Not Free." I used Bayesian methods for my analysis adding a percentage for the lack of freedom in the country. My prior was the percentage of votes Museveni garnered in the previous elections. I then used the amounted he had garnered in polls earlier last year, and then updated that calculation with the 51% of 2685 people polled in January. Adding the extra for the lack of freedom, This gave me Museveni's probability to be elected.

This article I think gives a good acount of overall situation in Uganda and the difficulty opposition will have in unseating Museveni. He basically controls all state apparatus and has a huge advantage in funding and wields power through corrupt institutions, especially the military and government as a whole. Uganda has never had a change of government through the ballot box. It appears the only thing that would unseat Museveni is his death, a coup (seems unlikely) or the opposition uniting somehow and combining their vote http://www.africa-confidential.com/article/id/11476/How_the_next_election_will_be_won
Museveni is a proven master of taking and retaining power and it is well documented he is using state power to increase his advantage.
It's all about profile in Africa.
If Besigye and Mbabazi had joined together the election might have been close. With voters divided it is more than likely that Museveni will win another term.
Museveni is the overwhelming favorite, and the opposition vote is split, working in his favor

Museveni's spending (unsurpringly) dwarfs that of his rivals*. And, while Museveni has had the audacity to complain about Besigye and Mbabazi trying to fix the election**, it's clear that most of the dirty tricks will be played by the incumbent. Museveni remains the overwhelming favorite here, in my opinion.
All the way

Museveni has a relative stranglehold on the country and has arrested several outspoken critics of the government in the lead up to the election. Also, Amama and Kizza decided to run on separate tickets, which will crucially split the opposition vote.
Yoweri Museveni istightening his grip on power and arresting outspoken protestors

Uganda has never had a change of government through the ballot box so its unlikely a change will result unless the government is overthrown militarily, the president dies or he retires. Mbabazi is probably the best candidate to win outside the President as he has brought supporters and networks with him after being dumped as Prime Minister from the ruling party

http://www.wsj.com/articles/heavily-armed-islamic-extremists-attack-peacekeepers-base-in-somalia-1452848795 UGANDAN FORCES PART OF AU EXPEDITIONARY FORCES TO SOMALIA. mugabe in zambia far worse. We may have to rely on enlightened despots like Kigali to evolve into a proto-democracy like Singapore...right now Kigali rule appears justified. See Burundi. Same with M in Uganda. Same with al-Sisi in Egypt, Saudis, UAE. and M is a lot better than US installed democratic in an autocrat state. See Iraq. No AU pressure on these autocrats. Contrast OAS mandate to Madura, free elections or isolation.

I think given the persistence of African leaders in countries like this give the incumbent a firm advantage the treatment of opposition parties lends itself to suggest the vote is likely to also be rigged. a 1% chance of None of the above seems to also be reasonable since he may die within the next month and that might lead open a gateway to a supporter of Yoweri Museveni. The main challenger seems to be Kizza Besigye who seems to be second place in the polls but given the chances of vote rigging
Update: No change in percentage of forecast.
want to remain above consensus on this
Moving up per @UnderwaterPutin.
The votes were counted 30 years ago.

Looks like Museveni is the incumbent, facing an independent challenger Mbabazi from his own party. The press seems to give Mbabazi a real chance, but I tend to under-rate challengers of a long-standing disliked regime unless they're obviously winning already (e.g. Trump levels of success). If not, I'll give it to the incumbent.
Updating based on latest poll information
Consensus is so high that there is little choice but to go higher.

American support appears to be falling off for YM -- last election the forum for democratic change (KB) took 30%+ of the vote. On the other hand there is notorious corruption involved (dead voters registered last time) and the electoral committee is appointed by YM
Upping YM from 99 to 100.

There's yet more reason to think that because of corruption Museveni will walk away with the victory regardless of how Ugandans actually vote#. And the US State Department certainly expects a lot of violence** to go along with the ballot box stuffing. But Mbabazi might have learned some tricks from his one-time boss*, and that could help him on the margins. Small advantage to both Museveni and Mbabazi over the other candidates on these considerations.
Fraud lead to repeat elections
Like Sibinsky(?) Commented. The fix is in. COUP would be only negation, 15%,probability.
no one seems to dispute that the fix is in, just in case. http://allafrica.com/stories/201601220651.html

Here's a bit of data I hadn't seen before: "a poll conducted earlier in 2015 suggested that the majority of Ugandans do not believe that it is possible to have a transfer of power through the ballot box"*. I couldn't find the poll itself (any help would be appreciated), but it suggests that many Ugandans who want change will be less motivated to vote than one might have otherwise expected. Advantage Museveni (at least in the election).

Museveni has been elected in the last 4 presidential elections. The electorate does not seem to be pining for change, especially since the Ugandan economy has remained relatively healthy under Museveni's rule. Besigye has failed to win the presidency despite running in the last three presidential elections -- he hasn't given the electorate a reason to vote for him this time since his present campaign message is largely the same as it was in his three former campaigns. Mbabazi, like Besigye, has been a known quantity in Ugandan politics for decades; his campaign, however, hasn't gained considerable traction and is perceived as incoherent. It s therefore quite likely that Museveni will win the election and remain in power.

Museveni and/or his supporters seem to be involved in attempted voter bribery*. This is not really shocking, but the fact that the campaign is doing this and getting away with it is welcome news for Museveni. And Museveni is spending _a lot_ of money (ca. $7 million in the last 2 months)** in a place where a little goes a long way. Finally, Uganda's currency is currently stable on world markets. If the markets were expecting change in this election cycle, we'd probably see movement here. The upshot: a slight increase in Museveni's likelihood of winning.
granularity

Given Museveni's hold on power (he's the classical strongman in the region, along with Rwanda's Paul Kagame and has been in power since 1986) I think there is a strong likelihood he will win the election by whatever means. Uganda has experienced robust economic growth and Museveni is kind of seen as a regional leader/troubleshooter, intervening in places like Burundi and Somalia. However, I think the recent Tanzanian election shows that incumbency is no longer as strong an advantage in an era of increased information flows. My initial hunch was to give Museveni the overwhelming advantage but I think his age, combined with anti-incumbency rhetoric in the region might contribute to Ugandans changing their minds.
Museveni and his "crime preventers" should remain in place after now 30 years of fraternity ...
Dropping some new poll numbers here: http://allafrica.com/stories/201601210165.html
Museveni far ahead in the polls
Six times elected? Not a chance. The voters will revolt. Hugh upset. Not predicted.
Death, revolution stand in Museveni's way. Museveni showing confidence (introducing biometrics, ditching debate) - but doesn't seem unwarranted when you control the vote and the press.
Museveni leads in the polls, and has the advantage of incumbancy.
I'm not sure how much faith to put into this opinion poll*, but it does contain some potentially interesting data:
Passage of time.

Ugandans' quality of life consistently improving under Museveni. Take a look at UNICEF's statistics on Uganda. Compared to Sub-Saharan Africa, Uganda is doing quite well. Departing from Museveni will be seen by some as a deviation from the (perceived) trajectory of growth and prosperity.
Close cooperation between US Army Africa Command and M.

30 year incumbent - having seen off a number of historical challenges greater than the one he currently faces (notably with poor coalition alignment towards end of 2015). My contacts on the ground in Uganda tell me its an 'absolute stone cold certainty' but nothing is 100% certain.

I believe that Museveni will be the winner of the Ugandan presidential election. It seems that his actions in the past, including changing the constitution to allow him to run again, reflect an attitude that he will do whatever it takes to keep his power intact. One caveat to keep in mind, though, is that we may see something reminiscent of recent unrest in the Middle East and North Africa that could inspire similar actions to overthrow the ruling government as his image has taken hits with silencing of opposition and political rivals (http://qz.com/469460/after-three-decades-in-power-ugandas-museveni-is-running-for-president-again/), which could lead to a victory by Mbabazi or Besigye, of course assuming that election results are reported fairly and accurately.
Corruption and vote rigging and/or suppression will lead to the ruling party retaining power
He hasn't done a bad job; isn't too unpopular - and is embedded. I just can't see him losing.
Marginally stronger than consensus

Bismarc notes that Museveni might die before the election, or that a televised debate might shake things up. Death is worth considering, but I very much doubt the debate will matter when YM controls the polls, is very popular, and has two opposition candidates splitting the vote against him.

Presidential debate took place on Friday, but Museveni didn't bother to show up. If you think you're going to win big, maybe you don't need to show up. This was the first time for a Presidential candidate debate in Uganda. It probably won't have much impact since Museveni seems to have a strong arm on the press. If a tree falls in the forest, but no one is there to hear it, does it make a sound? If a debate happens, and no one dares to report on it, does it make any noise? http://www.worldbulletin.net/haber/168286/uganda-media-intimidated-ahead-of-presidential-polls

There's a little more reason to think that the opposition candidates are largely taking vote shares from each other#, more or less as expected. That said, Mbabazi seems to be gaining a bit of traction in the Mayuge district##, which improves his chances slightly, at Museveni's expense.

The current president has assured observers that the coming election will be free and fair. However, the president has been in power for nearly thirty years. Only a few sub-Saharan countries have had peaceful regime changes in a situation where the president has had power for this long. Amama Mbabazi was a member of the current presidents' party. However, he is no longer a member so it is unlikely he will win.
Nothing very major against him thus far, that is new or stunning. Split opposition will help him.
Following Lars Ericson's supercrowd. https://larswericson.wordpress.com/

At the recent debate, Mbabazi had difficulty separating himself from some past actions of Museveni's gov't.* That can't be good for him, but I don't think it drops him below a 2% probability of winning.

• campaign violence and intimidation will favour incumbent by keeping voters at home; introduction of biometric screening to vote will keep non-incumbent supporters out of voting system • the 3 candidates look less dissimilar than might be warranted in order to get many people to the polls • 2011: Museveni won with 68% of the vote; Besigye received 26% • Museveni is “heavily favoured” and has overseen sustained economic growth (though slowing); Besigye is popular and admired (but has run and lost 4 times) so will generally retain similar poll %; Mbabazi split from Museveni’s party and therefore will likely pick up a few opposition votes from Besigye and will peel off a larger % of Museveni votes

One reason to think there's more uncertainty around this election than expected can be found in a recent Reuters article. On the one hand, Museveni is "heavily favored to win another five-year term at polls next month," yet just a few sentences later we are told that the "election is expected to be one of the toughest yet for Museveni."* Both claims _could_ be true, but there's a lot of tension between them. And the fact that the debate was held without Museveni is also a slight embarrassment for him. I'm inclined to downgrade the likelihood of a Museveni victory slightly because of all of this.

Museveni rules as a dictator in all but name. He is a strong-man leader who took power by deposing other dictators. Museveni also has a history of bullying, interfering with, and harassing political opponents and their supporters, as has been widely reported by Human Rights groups outside Uganda. History shows that most strong-men leaders only lead office by dying or through revolution.
Museveni a no-show for first-ever presidential debate (+5)
Besigye did well in the debate.

I suspect that the voting system is a bit corrupt but the ruling party will remain in power with a new leader (Mbabazi). I don't think the independent Besigye has the type of public recognition that makes him seem a good leader. I do think that Museveni's suppression of his opposition will be what kicks him out this time.
Museveni has beaten Besigye 3 times and is only 71 (relatively).

Besigye's decision to attend the debate* may be somewhat embarrassing to Museveni, who's skipping it. It will also give Besigye a chance to score points against Museveni publicly and without facing a direct rebuttal. Small advantage to Besigye. Despite that fact, Museveni would still probably be better off not attending the debate since he has little to gain here and much to lose. The best outcome for him would be one in which everyone refused to participate in the debate, but that looks much less likely now. At any rate, high levels of violence are reasonable to expect - very disturbing.**
Museveni is only 71 years old. He won by 68% majority in the last election and he has had sustained economic growth.

Museveni has beaten Besigye 3 times in a row. Besigye has claimed that the election was rigged and Museveni has been accused of multiple accounts of corruption. There is also a poll that says that 71.7% of Ugandans said that they would reelect Museveni. However, the poll only asked 6,580 of the 37.58 million people living in Uganda and it did not provide them with options to choose from.

Museveni will use whatever methods necessary to win the election. He has enough support via patronage and desire for stability to establish credibility. If necessary, he'll use other methods to seal victory. Besigye was runner-up in the last 2 elections and has wide support, just not enough for victory.

Uganda for years suffered from Civil War. Museveni has brought some measure of calm, Uganda is now surrounded by countries that dangerous and have widespread death from disease and war. Ugandan economy is also growing. On the merits, it appears that Museveni deserves another term. However, it appears that Museveni is not taking any chances and will use what other means possible to fix the election if he has to.

In an Erdoğan text book approach, Yoweri Museveni is intimidating the press, human rights groups, and the opposition who are too fractured to defeat him in polls. He was president for 30 years and runs all the major institutions.

Museveni's pulling out of the presidential debate* doesn't appear to hurt him but removes an opportunity for the other candidates to score points against him. Some banks in involved with Uganda seem uncertain about the election,** but if they have good reason, they're not (to the best of my knowledge) sharing it. So small advantage to Museveni.

Black Star News reports, "Although there are no reliable polls, judging by the massive turnouts at the oppositions' campaign rallies, the dictator is in the run of his life. Ugandans are also witnessing something never seen before. Ordinary citizens attending Dr. Besigye's rallies pull hard-earned money from their pockets for the challenger to help fund his campaign."* The report seems based on anecdote alone, but it makes me think that Besigye has a slightly better chance than I had previously believed.
If he dies before the election I will change my forecast.

Museveni is flexing his muscles against journalists.* Does this show that he's in control or that he's just trying to give that impression by targeting a highly visible and vulnerable group? I'm beginning to suspect it's a bit more of the latter than the former. The Guardian reports that "Uganda’s key demographic group comprises under-30s, who account for up to 80% of the population. Their trust in Museveni’s brand of one-man democracy is uncertain."** A clear victory for Museveni almost certainly requires keeping many younger voters away from the polls. As Amnesty International reports (alarmingly for friends of democracy), Museveni seems to be on the road to doing that effectively.*** One thing to watch for: Museveni crack downs go so far that they generate a large backlash. We'll see.
Sounds like plenty of violence and intimidation. +5 for Museveni.

Given Museveni’s apparent degree of control over the elections themselves, much of the data that would be useful for forecasting a fair election is largely irrelevant. Museveni’s opponents face a number of challenges above and beyond the amount of control that Museveni has over the elections: (1) the opposition is divided, (2) reforms to the system seem unlikely before the next election. Museveni’s main challenge seems to be to remain in control of the process, something he is currently doing handily.

Only a united opposition can unseat Museveni. Mbabazi has what Besigye lacks, which is insiders in the govt. Having played major roles in Museveni's govt for many years he knows where the weaknesses are. The failure of the two main challengers to form an alliance means Museveni will remain in power.

African elections are just a farce. I do not expect Uganda to be different, A quote attributed to Museveni as advice to Ghadaffi: "Revolutionaries never retire." If that is the case, how can a revolutionary lose an election, supervised by his very own government? It is like referee-player giving himself a red-card during a soccer match. Not going to happen.

Inumbency has its "priveleges." http://www.theafricareport.com/East-Horn-Africa/handicapping-the-2016-ugandan-presidential-election.html Poll of women only back in June 2015 sex outsider House Speaker Rebecca Kadaga could be a factor in future. http://www.elections.co.ug/static/polls

Given South Sudan Sudan, Libya. Somalia, US not actively pressuring for a free election. Hear no complaints from any Governments. Or press. Will supply links from voa, and wsj later.

@Pstauble: your structured analysis gave me some additional insights i was missing out in mine. All in all, it reinforces my own judgement, answering the question. The elections will take place as foreseen and Musuveni will win it for almost sure. If he dies because of age or assassination can be, but the timeline until the election is extremely short, and the likelihood of such an occurrence very small I judge. I therefore see no need to change my current vote
Crowd surfing
Incumbent victory

Initial forecast. Seems like Yoweri has all the levers to ensure a smooth transition (i.e. Parliment and Government) and the main rival is from his party so little support likely from that quarter is this is similar to not free type electorial contests so I would put it at a high probability (90%). If not established party/power structure would likely gravitate around Mbabazi who has held senior key positions.
Uganda has no level playing field in electoral competition
Museveni still controls this state completely
The fix is in. This is an authoritarian regime that does many things to ensure elections are not competitive, and this year's presidential contest almost certainly won't break that pattern.
A small wonder might throw Museveni out of the saddle, but that sort of guy usually stays...
In countries with long-time rulers, machine corruption tends to keep them in power.
Obote, Idid Amin, Museveni - all came to power by coup and left by coup. I couldn't find any peaceful handing o power. That's our prior: 100% for the incumbent.

"The Electoral Commission is virtually the same as the one from 2011..." "...widespread apathy. “Elections have become a ritual in recent years,”" " At the last election in 2011 turnout was just 59%, down from 71% in 2001." "Partly thanks to long suppression, the opposition is weak and divided." --------------------------------------------------------------- Sources
read the top comments and those with links. 2.5mo until the election doesn't give much time.

While AM might have a smallchance, he still is a newcomer in the presidential race. KB has already lost 2 elections and is most likely seen as somewhat of a sore loser. Added to that, the election resukts of 2011 vs 2006 show one of two things: 1. The 1.5 mil more voters i 2011 were either 0.5 mil from KB with an added 1 mil voters in favor of YM; or. 2. KB lost 0.5 mil voters, while YM got an extra of 1.5 mil compared to 2011. With an expected somewhat low participation, an with YM showing that he has about 40% of total possible votes... there can be only one winner.aa Add to that the tendency of the populace to go ahead with the known when nothing exceptional and negative towards the status quo shakes them of inertia, while things are perceived as being ok.

Chances are very big that Museveni will hold on to power through force, however a mutiny might give Mbabazi or Bisgye a chance. A small probability exists that AU will deploy a peaceforce a appoint a caretaker.
I updated this forecast (see 11:27 am) and wanted to cancel this "draft" but haven't found "delete" option (I've just joined and tried how everything works here)
http://allafrica.com/stories/201601042297.html

Uganda ranks 142 on the Transparency International corruption Index, previous electiona have been judged as corrupt. So the probability is that this election will be corrupt, so that even if other candidates got more votes (which seems unlikely) Museveni would still "win". Mbabazi in an interview appeared to be be saying he supports Museveni - an unusual thing for a rival candidate to say. So unless Museveni decides he no longer wants to be President he will win the election. If he were to decide to give up or dies before the vote then it is possible that no election will be held and someone else (his son?) could emerge.
Though there are signs of a divide in the NRM, Museveni's dominance and the lack of an organised, united opposition makes his success in the 2016 election highly likely.

Numerous forecasters have detailed the strengths of the incumbent - most compelling for me in reviewing them were the indications of real economic growth under the incumbent, his deeply-established political machine, ubiquity in name recognition, well-founded cynicism and thus turn-out apathy among the opposition.
Museveni has won by wide margins in the past and current polls show his lead is almost unclosable. Will update with more details.

The first thing that I did was to look at a map and find out where Uganda is. The next thing I did, was to look at some data from a variety of sources. I decided to approach the situation by comparing the data between now and the last Ugandan elections, in the hope that this would give me a bit of an objective comparison, however this was quite difficult in many cases. The most interesting data that I found was: Transparency International has rated Uganda's public sector as one of the most corrupt in the world. In 2014, Uganda ranked 142nd worst out of 175 and had a score of 26 on a scale from 0 (perceived as most corrupt) to 100 (perceived as clean). GDP per capita has increased from 2.6% in 2012 to 4.8% in 2014. 2/3 of the work force work in agriculture. The main export is coffee. Oil has been found but will only start being produced locally in 2017: http://www.reuters.com/article/uganda-oil-idUSL6N0NV4AW20140509. Import partners: Kenya 18.3%, UAE 14.3%, India 12.8%, China 11.3%, Japan 4.4% (2014). Export Partners: Rwanda 10.1%, UAE 9.8%, Democratic Republic of the Congo 9.3%, Kenya 9.1%, Netherlands 6%, Germany 5.7%, Italy 5.5%, China 5.3% (2014). Uganda has soldiers deployed in the northern and eastern areas of the Democratic Republic of the Congo and in the Central African Republic, Somalia, and South Sudan. The number of internally displaced persons is estimated at 1.4 million. Population of ca 37 million Ethnic Groups: 17.4% Baganda, 9.8% Banyankole, 8.4% Basoga, 7.0% Bakiga, 6.1% Iteso, 3.2% Langi, 4.8% Acholi, 4.1% Bagisu, 4.14% Lugbara, 33.3% others. The next research I did was on the incumbent, Yoweri Museveni, the strongman of Uganda. He has been in power since 1986. Despite the fact that he is a tough leader, with a questionable human rights record, he has massively boosted the Ugandan economy and defeated most of the rebels within his country. He has good control over the military: his son leads the special forces, a great deal of the military has been trained by US forces (at least those that have been deployed to Somalia) and most political, military and judiciary leaders are affiliated with him in some way. Museveni also controls the supreme court. Although the judges are elected by parliament, the supreme court judges are all chosen by Museveni. This has a great deal of importance because it is the supreme court that decides whether an election is invalidated or not (http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/4882594.stm). It should be noted that election fraud is quite common, and the supreme court has ruled in almost every election year in the past that there have been irregularities, however they have not annulled any of the election results, as they have stated that the fraud did not significantly affect the outcome of the elections (http://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2011-02-20/museveni-extends-25-year-rule-in-uganda-election-opponents-reject-result). Since taking over Uganda Museveni has massively improved the quality of life of the majority of his people (excluding some minorities and political opponents). To summarize: Museveni has control of a well trained Army, regularly participates in rigging elections (and is quite good at it), intimidates oponents (http://allafrica.com/stories/201512161117.html, http://www.geeskaafrika.com/uganda-violence-looms-large-in-campaigns/13978/) and seems to be genuinely quite popular (http://www.elections.co.ug/static/afro-barometer-poll). Most importantly, the majority of people in Uganda don’t really have that much of an incentive to not vote for Museveni - he has literally pulled his country out of the ashes. This leads me to ask the question: what could happen that would cause the incumbent to lose the election? I think there are three ways that he could lose the election. The first, is that more people simply vote for one of the contenders. The second option, is that there is some kind of armed revolution that would lead to Museveni being toppled AND the elections still taking place. Finally, I think a likely possibility is that Museveni dies before the election. For one of the other candidates to be elected, it would have to mean that they have widespread support among the people that is so high, that it overcomes any election rigging, while not being so high that Museveni cancels the election. Currently, I do not think that any of the alternative candidates have the popular support required to have a significant enough impact to achieve this. Added to this, with such an ethnically divided country it would be very difficult to get widespread support in such a short time. If a candidate had this support, I think it would already be more clearly reflected in the polls and in the media. I think it is possible that another candidate may be able to mobilise the younger generations of ugandans (who now can register to vote online http://pctechmag.com/2015/08/uganda-electoral-commission-introduces-online-voter-verification-ahead-of-2016-polls/). However, I have not found any evidence that any of the candidates has an especially large or relevant grassroots movement amongst young Ugandans (and all of the front runners are part of the “old” establishment, so probably not particularly motivating to young ugandans). On the other hand, the Ugandan Electoral system is a two round system, so if Museveni gets less than 50% of the vote, he will run off against the second place candidate. This means that in theory, all voters could go against Museveni, giving the other candidate the majority of the vote. I doubt this will happen, on the one hand, because Museveni would ensure that the elections are rigged in his favour, on the other, because the incumbent would make sure to trade favours for support in a run off, and finally, I do not think Museveni will get less than 50%, based on the polls and his past support. His largest contender is Kizza Besigye, who has already lost several times in a row. The current polls do not seem to indicate that this will change. Besigye threatened violence and revolution after his last loss, however even his own party and affiliated MPs did not support him, which pushes my theory that the general sentiment of the people and politicians in Uganda is to keep making the most of the rather good status quo. The new runner in the race is Amama Mbabazi, former Prime Minister and confidant of Museveni. I think that Mbabazis chances are even lower. He does not even breach the 5% mark in the polls, and is running as an independent with no loyal party base to push him forward. Additionally, he just disbanded a large part of his electiont team: http://allafrica.com/stories/201512161307.html The second reason he could lose the election, is if there is some kind of armed revolt, but the elections still take place. I think that this is very unlikely. I’m a big fan of the greed vs. grievance model put forward by Paul Collier and Anke Hoeffler. Museveni has managed to ensure that fighting against the status quo has a very high opportunity cost. Obviously, there is the possibility that some oppressed minority or the large population of IDPs pick up arms and start a revolution. However, even if this did occur, I think it may even help Museveni, as it would give him an opportunity to show strength. Also, the timeframe and probability of a revolt taking place, for Museveni to be overthrown and the elections to still take place, is quite unrealistic in my opinion. Finally, Museveni has good relations with many of his neighbours, with the African Union, with the US and Russia (although he also has bad relations with other neighbours). I cannot identify any external players who is proactively pushing for a revolution or for Museveni to lose the election. The final reason he may lose the election, is if he dies. I think an assassination attempt is not unlikely, especially by one of his enemies (Besigye has threatened violence on numerous occasions). However, the presidential guard is extremely loyal, lead by his son and very well trained. I think if Museveni has survived the last 30 years of leadership (and, as a quick google search shows, several assassination attempts), he will be able to survive until the election. Additionally, I am sure that there will be increased security in the run up to the election. On the other hand Museveni has done publicity stunts in the past where he is extremely exposed, such as driving himself to polling stations. The other reason he may die, is simply because he is an old man. I have not found much about his health status, but at over 70 years old he is already above the average Ugandan life expectancy (not unusual, as he probably has above average doctors and access to medical care). Nonetheless, it isn't a risk that can be ignored. However, if he does die by assassination or old age, I do not think that Mbabazi or Besigye would win. Instead I think that Musevenis son, who is allegedly being groomed to take his place (http://www.reuters.com/article/us-uganda-politics-idUSBRE94J0F420130520?feedType=RSS&feedName=worldNews) will take his father's place on the ballot. For this to happen, Museveni would have to die soon, the election committee (I assume also controlled by Museveni's family) and Supreme Court (controlled by Museveni) would have to allow Museveni's son to take his father's place on the ballot. It is also possible, that Museveni dies, and Mbabazi comes back into the fold and takes Museveni's place as the head of the NRM, and then takes his votes. All of these events are quite unlikely, although not completely impossible. I think it is a higher possibility that in the event of Museveni's death there is a coup, the army takes control, or some type of internal power struggle occurs, causing the elections to be postponed or delayed.

He has a tight grip on the country and has been in power about 30 years and has full authority to write laws and detain opposition. His opposition is not organized to where they could defeat the leader of a country which is 142 of 175 in the most corrupt nation index, which is 2 points higher than the previous year on the transparency index database (Transparency International, 2015). Assuming he doesn't die between now and then, Museveni runs a country inconsequential enough that international monitors will cry about good governance, etc. like so many voices in the wilderness. Plus, the worldwide perception of turmoil at every border will make anyone who has a demonstrable record of stability highly favored in an election. Lastly, Uganda's economy, though teeny, has strong fundamentals. It trades largely within Africa, its imports have benefited from super low prices (petroleum!), its exports largely track global growth trends in terms of volatility, and its citizens' mobile usage rides the wave of leapfrogging landlines, thus ensuring it the country remains relevant in the same way Kenya, etc. have used this reality to boost GDP.
